</article><!-- #post-5543 -->
<hr class="post-separator" aria-hidden="true" />
<article id="post-5524" class="post-5524 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-feature-from-the-collections category-sc">
			<header class="entry-header">
			<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/">The Top 8 Odd and Outstanding Artist’s Books in Ryerson’s Special Collections</a></h1>
		</header><!-- .entry-header -->
	
	<div class="entry-content">

				<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="sep">Posted on </span><a href="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/" title="11:35 am" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2016-01-11T11:35:47-05:00" pubdate>January 11, 2016</time></a><span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/author/askyrme/" title="View all posts by Alison" rel="author">Alison</a></span></span>		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
		
		<p>Ryerson&#8217;s Special Collections is filled with all kinds of unique and unusual material. Here is our list of the top 8 odd and outstanding artist&#8217;s books you can find in our collection!</p>
<p><a href="http://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/dsc_0506a/" rel="attachment wp-att-5525"><img data-attachment-id="5525" data-permalink="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/dsc_0506a/" data-orig-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0506a.jpg" data-orig-size="1203,800" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;11&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;NIKON D40&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1449246062&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;30&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;800&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.003125&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="DSC_0506a" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0506a-300x200.jpg" data-large-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0506a-600x399.jpg" loading="lazy" class="alignright size-large wp-image-5525" src="http://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0506a-600x399.jpg" alt="DSC_0506a" width="600" height="399" srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0506a-600x399.jpg 600w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0506a-150x100.jpg 150w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0506a-300x200.jpg 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0506a.jpg 1203w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></a></p>
<ol start="8">
<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="http://catalogue.library.ryerson.ca/record=b1458395~S0">Scratch by Christian Boltanski</a></span></li>
</ol>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This thin artist’s book allegedly contains ten duotones of forbidden images. However, what the reader will see when browsing this book is a stiff book with five silver coloured pages. That&#8217;s because Boltanski has coated each image in a scratch-card like opaque substance. So, the only way to view the hidden images is to physically scratch off the surface of each page. In this way, the artist is making a statement about the responsibility of viewing images of disaster, forcing the reader to make a decision &#8211; either peek and look, or stare and wonder at what lies beneath the surface.</span></p>
<p><a href="http://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/dsc_0495a/" rel="attachment wp-att-5526"><img data-attachment-id="5526" data-permalink="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/dsc_0495a/" data-orig-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0495a.jpg" data-orig-size="1203,800" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;11&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;NIKON D40&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1449245836&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;28&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;800&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.003125&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="DSC_0495a" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0495a-300x200.jpg" data-large-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0495a-600x399.jpg" loading="lazy" class="alignright size-large wp-image-5526" src="http://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0495a-600x399.jpg" alt="DSC_0495a" width="600" height="399" srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0495a-600x399.jpg 600w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0495a-150x100.jpg 150w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0495a-300x200.jpg 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0495a.jpg 1203w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></a></p>
<ol start="7">
<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="http://catalogue.library.ryerson.ca/record=b1728735~S0">Cock Fight Dance by Sol LeWitt</a></span></li>
</ol>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sol LeWitt was one of the artists spearheading the Conceptual movement in the 1960s. While he was most well-known for his painting, drawing and sculpture works, LeWitt also published multiple photographic artist’s books. This odd little book contains a photographic narrative of two roosters fighting. With a simple layout and premise, this book of photographs light-heartedly hints at dance and performance. Because the whole event is not completely recorded, LeWitt’s book suggests multiple readings and multiple endings.</span></p>
<p><a href="http://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/dsc_0533a/" rel="attachment wp-att-5527"><img data-attachment-id="5527" data-permalink="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/dsc_0533a/" data-orig-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0533a.jpg" data-orig-size="1203,800" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;11&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;NIKON D40&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1449246609&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;32&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;800&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.003125&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="DSC_0533a" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0533a-300x200.jpg" data-large-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0533a-600x399.jpg" loading="lazy" class="alignright size-large wp-image-5527" src="http://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0533a-600x399.jpg" alt="DSC_0533a" width="600" height="399" srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0533a-600x399.jpg 600w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0533a-150x100.jpg 150w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0533a-300x200.jpg 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0533a.jpg 1203w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></a></p>
<ol start="6">
<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="http://catalogue.library.ryerson.ca/record=b1796442~S0">See by Marcia Resnick</a></span></li>
</ol>
<p><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">See</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> by Marcia Resnick contains 34 black and white portraits. Each portrait shows the subject in the center of the frame in front of various landscapes. However, instead of looking at the camera, each subject has their back to us. This simple little book from 1975 can actually be read as a deeper exploration of looking and being look at, of seeing and being seen.</span></p>
<p><a href="http://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/dsc_0510a/" rel="attachment wp-att-5528"><img data-attachment-id="5528" data-permalink="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/dsc_0510a/" data-orig-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0510a.jpg" data-orig-size="1203,800" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;11&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;NIKON D40&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1449246168&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;52&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;800&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.003125&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="DSC_0510a" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0510a-300x200.jpg" data-large-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0510a-600x399.jpg" loading="lazy" class="alignright size-large wp-image-5528" src="http://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0510a-600x399.jpg" alt="DSC_0510a" width="600" height="399" srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0510a-600x399.jpg 600w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0510a-150x100.jpg 150w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0510a-300x200.jpg 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0510a.jpg 1203w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></a></p>
<ol start="5">
<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="http://catalogue.library.ryerson.ca/record=b1955296~S0">Rainbow in Your Hand by Masashi Kawamura</a></span></li>
</ol>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">It won’t take long for you to read this book cover-to-cover, and it’s definitely one you’ll want to peruse again! At first, this artist’s book seems a bit underwhelming &#8211; each of its pages are completely identical with small coloured squares on each side of a black page. However, everything changes once the reader realizes it is actually a flipbook &#8211; and not a conventional flipbook either. Instead of creating an illusion of movement on the pages, this book creates a three-dimensional illusion. When this clever little book is flipped though, a rainbow appears in the space between the pages!</span></p>
<p><a href="http://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/dsc_0526a/" rel="attachment wp-att-5529"><img data-attachment-id="5529" data-permalink="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/dsc_0526a/" data-orig-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0526a.jpg" data-orig-size="1203,800" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;11&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;NIKON D40&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1449246544&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;22&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;800&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.003125&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="DSC_0526a" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0526a-300x200.jpg" data-large-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0526a-600x399.jpg" loading="lazy" class="alignright size-large wp-image-5529" src="http://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0526a-600x399.jpg" alt="DSC_0526a" width="600" height="399" srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0526a-600x399.jpg 600w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0526a-150x100.jpg 150w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0526a-300x200.jpg 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0526a.jpg 1203w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></a></p>
<ol start="4">
<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="http://catalogue.library.ryerson.ca/record=b1192982~S0">Hide by Fred Escher</a></span></li>
</ol>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This book is a great example of the type of unconventional book that was published by conceptual artists in the 1970s. The book contains black and white photographs, each of the artist hiding in plain sight. Part-performance, part-photography, the work Escher creates in this book shows the landscape and artist as merged, and can be seen to the reader as a sort of grown-up version of Where’s Waldo.</span></p>
<p><a href="http://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/dsc_0500a/" rel="attachment wp-att-5530"><img data-attachment-id="5530" data-permalink="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/dsc_0500a/" data-orig-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0500a.jpg" data-orig-size="1203,800" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;11&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;NIKON D40&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1449245948&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;28&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;800&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.003125&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="DSC_0500a" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0500a-300x200.jpg" data-large-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0500a-600x399.jpg" loading="lazy" class="alignright size-large wp-image-5530" src="http://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0500a-600x399.jpg" alt="DSC_0500a" width="600" height="399" srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0500a-600x399.jpg 600w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0500a-150x100.jpg 150w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0500a-300x200.jpg 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0500a.jpg 1203w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></a></p>
<ol start="3">
<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="http://catalogue.library.ryerson.ca/record=b2502481~S0">Mountain Dream Tarot by Bea Nettles</a></span></li>
</ol>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This collection of images</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">firmly resides outside of the traditional form of artist’s book. Instead of bound pages, this work consists of 78 individual tarot cards. The deck from 1975 is the first known photographic tarot deck, and is one of the most collectible tarot card decks in the world. Using herself, as well as family and friends as models, the artist created the multicoloured photographic cards over the span of 5 years. A lot of skill and technique went into each image. There was no Photoshop at the time, so Nettles used darkroom tricks to create special effects in the images &#8211; collaged photographs, multi-layered images and hand-drawn symbols are some of the processes she employed.</span></p>
<p><a href="http://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/dsc_0519a/" rel="attachment wp-att-5531"><img data-attachment-id="5531" data-permalink="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/dsc_0519a/" data-orig-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0519a.jpg" data-orig-size="1203,800" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;11&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;NIKON D40&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1449246379&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;40&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;800&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.003125&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="DSC_0519a" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0519a-300x200.jpg" data-large-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0519a-600x399.jpg" loading="lazy" class="alignright size-large wp-image-5531" src="http://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0519a-600x399.jpg" alt="DSC_0519a" width="600" height="399" srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0519a-600x399.jpg 600w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0519a-150x100.jpg 150w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0519a-300x200.jpg 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0519a.jpg 1203w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></a></p>
<ol start="2">
<li><a href="http://catalogue.library.ryerson.ca/record=b1102049~S0"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Octogonal Houses of Maine by </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Carol-Lynn Rössel Waugh</span></a></li>
</ol>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This curious book is by far the smallest in the collection &#8211; in fact it measures just 2 centimeters by 2.5 centimeters! The book chronicles the history of the eight-sided homes in the state of Maine. The author appears to have also written multiple books on the subject of teddy bears, and is a self-proclaimed &#8220;teddy bear artist&#8221;. In addition to being the smallest book in our collection, we consider it to be one of the oddest little gems in the stacks!</span></p>
<p><a href="http://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/dsc_0514a/" rel="attachment wp-att-5532"><img data-attachment-id="5532" data-permalink="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/2016/01/the-top-8-odd-and-outstanding-artists-books-in-ryersons-special-collections/dsc_0514a/" data-orig-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0514a.jpg" data-orig-size="1203,800" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;11&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;NIKON D40&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1449246248&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;40&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;800&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.003125&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="DSC_0514a" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0514a-300x200.jpg" data-large-file="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0514a-600x399.jpg" loading="lazy" class="alignright size-large wp-image-5532" src="http://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0514a-600x399.jpg" alt="DSC_0514a" width="600" height="399" srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0514a-600x399.jpg 600w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0514a-150x100.jpg 150w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0514a-300x200.jpg 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/asc/files/2015/12/DSC_0514a.jpg 1203w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></a></p>
<ol>
<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="http://catalogue.library.ryerson.ca/record=b1022637~S0">Every Building on the Sunset Strip by Ed Ruscha</a></span></li>
</ol>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This rare and fragile artist’s book is one of the most iconic to come out of the 1970s. For </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Every Building on the Sunset Strip, </span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;">the artist mounted a motorized camera to the back of a truck, photographing every building he passed. Ruscha then created a bound accordion-style book from one continuous folding strip that extends approximately 25 feet. Though now the book might make us think of Google Street View, the book revealed at the time a new form of topographical map-making study. Ruscha is known for spearheading a new genre of artist’s book, favouring a cheap and conceptual approach over the typical </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">livre d’artiste </span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;">of the day. Ryerson’s Special Collections is also home to various other original seminal Ruscha books, including </span><a href="http://catalogue.library.ryerson.ca/record=b1783395~S0"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Business Cards</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, </span><a href="http://catalogue.library.ryerson.ca/record=b1716227~S0"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Royal Road Test</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> and </span><a href="http://catalogue.library.ryerson.ca/record=b1716386~S0"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Crackers</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">. </span></p>
<p><a href="mailto:archives@ryerson.ca"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Contact us</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> to come have a look at these odd and outstanding artist’s books!</span></p>
